      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nI ran into [[Ward Cunningham]] and [[Kent Beck]] the next year at OOPSLA '88, at another of [[Norm Kerth]]'s workshops. I recall sitting in back after watching one of the SADT/process carpetbaggers who'd descended on the then frontier of O-O tell people that if they built software the same old way, but with object oriented languages, they'd get reuse and productivity for free. I was appalled at the positive reception they received. As the room emptied Ward and Kent (who, like myself, were iconclasts Norm had put on the program to stir things up) started talking about this architect named Christopher Alexander who wrote this book that described how to build your own house the way you wanted by going down this list of \"patterns\", and making choices as you went. Wouldn't it be great to have something like this for software, said they. ",
